definition.value: A class of nuclear body, first seen after silver staining by Ramon y Cajal in 1903, enriched in small nuclear ribonucleoproteins, and certain general RNA polymerase II transcription factors -  ultrastructurally, they appear as a tangle of coiled, electron-dense threads roughly 0.5 micrometers in diameter -  involved in aspects of snRNP biogenesis -  the protein coilin serves as a marker for Cajal bodies. Some argue that Cajal bodies are the sites for preassembly of transcriptosomes, unitary particles involved in transcription and processing of RNA.
Catalysis of the reaction -  a protein with reduced sulfide groups -eq- a protein with oxidized disulfide bonds.
Catalysis of the reaction -  substrate with reduced sulfide groups -eq- substrate with oxidized disulfide bonds.
Catalysis of the reaction -  a peptide with reduced sulfide groups -eq- a peptide with oxidized disulfide bonds.
Catalysis of the reaction -  2 glutathione + electron acceptor -eq- glutathione disulfide + electron donor.
Catalysis of the reaction -  oxidized adrenodoxin + NADPH + H+ -eq- reduced adrenodoxin + NADP+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  NADP+ + trypanothione -eq- NADPH + H+ + trypanothione disulfide.
Catalysis of the reaction -  NADPH + H+ + 2 ferrileghemoglobin -eq- NADP+ + 2 ferroleghemoglobin.
Catalysis of the reaction -  reduced rubredoxin + NAD+ -eq- oxidized rubredoxin + NADH + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  reduced rubredoxin + NAD(P)+ -eq- oxidized rubredoxin + NAD(P)H + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  reduced rubredoxin + NADP+ -eq- oxidized rubredoxin + NADPH + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  NADPH + H+ + 2 ferricytochrome c2 -eq- NADP+ + 2 ferrocytochrome c2.

Catalysis of the transfer of electrons between pyridine nucleotides (obligatory two-electron carriers) and hemes or (2Fe-2S) centers (obligatory one-electron carriers) in respiration, photosynthesis, and many oxygenase systems.
Catalysis of the reaction -  methane + NAD(P)H + H+ + O2 -eq- methanol + NAD(P)+ + H2O.
A protein complex that possesses methane monooxygenase activity -  dimeric and trimeric complexes have been characterized.
Combining with epinephrine or norepinephrine to initiate a change in cell activity via activation of a G protein, with pharmacological characteristics of beta3-adrenergic receptors.
Combining with gastrin and transmitting the signal across the membrane by activating an associated G-protein to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with secretin to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with the corticotrophin-releasing factor family of ligands, including the urocortins, to initiate a change in cell activity.

Combining with thrombin to initiate a G-protein mediated change in cell activity. A G-protein is a signal transduction molecule that alternates between an inactive GDP-bound and an active GTP-bound state.
Combining with UTP or UDP to initiate a change in cell activity.
Stops, prevents or reduces the activity of alpha-amylase.
Catalysis of the reversible transfer of an amidino group to an acceptor.
Catalysis of the reaction -  L-arginine + glycine -eq- L-ornithine + guanidinoacetate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  1-amino-1-deoxy-scyllo-inositol 4-phosphate + L-arginine -eq- 1-guanidino-1-deoxy-scyllo-inositol 4-phosphate + L-ornithine.
Catalysis of the transfer of an ion from one side of a membrane to the other.

label.value: monovalent inorganic cation transmembrane transporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a inorganic cations with a valency of one from one side of a membrane to the other. Inorganic cations are atoms or small molecules with a positive charge that do not contain carbon in covalent linkage.
Catalysis of the transfer of hydrogen ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of potassium ions (K+) from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of silver (Ag) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of sodium ions (Na+) from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of aluminum (Al) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of calcium (Ca) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of cadmium (Cd) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of cobalt (Co) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  Cu+(out) -eq- Cu+(in).

label.value: high-affinity copper ion transmembrane transporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  Cu2+(out) -eq- Cu2+(in). In high-affinity transport the transporter is able to bind the solute even if it is only present at very low concentrations.

label.value: low-affinity iron ion transmembrane transporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  Fe2+(out) -eq- Fe2+(in). In low-affinity transport the transporter is able to bind the solute only if it is present at very high concentrations.
Catalysis of the transfer of ferric iron (Fe(III) or Fe3+) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.

label.value: high-affinity ferric uptake transmembrane transporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of Fe(III) from the outside of a cell to the inside of a cell across a membrane. In high-affinity transport the transporter is able to bind the solute even if it is only present at very low concentrations.
Catalysis of the transfer of ferrous iron (Fe(II) or Fe2+) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of lead (Pb) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of magnesium (Mg) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of mercury (Hg) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of molybdate (MoO4 2-) ions from one side of a membrane to the other. Molybdate is the bivalent anion derived from molybdic acid.
Catalysis of the transfer of nickel (Ni) cations from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of vanadium (V) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of organic cations from one side of a membrane to the other. Organic cations are atoms or small molecules with a positive charge that contain carbon in covalent linkage.

Catalysis of the transfer of inorganic anions from one side of a membrane to the other. Inorganic anions are atoms or small molecules with a negative charge which do not contain carbon in covalent linkage.
Catalysis of the transfer of antimonite from one side of a membrane to the other.
